–1273","1240–1273":"1240–1273","1230–1303":"1230–1303","1260–Female":"1260–Overleden","1270–1304":"1270–1304","1272–Male":"1272–Overleden","1273–Male":"1273–Overleden","1215–1240":"1215–1240","ABT 1260":"circa 1260","1304":"1304","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1303":"1303","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1273":"1273","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","about 1240":"circa 1240","Castle Cary,,,England":"Castle Cary, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","South Tawton, Devon, England":"South Tawton, Devon, England","England":"England","Castle Cary, Somersetshire, England":"Castle Cary, Somerset, England","South Taughton, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"about 1240–1273":"about 1240–1273","1240–1273":"1240–1273","1230–1303":"1230–1303","1260–Female":"1260–Deceased","1270–1304":"1270–1304","1272–Male":"1272–Deceased","1273–Male":"1273–Deceased","1215–1240":"1215–1240","ABT 1260":"about 1260","1304":"1304","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1303":"1303","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1273":"1273","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","about 1240":"about 1240","Castle Cary,,,England":"Castle Cary, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","South Tawton, Devon, England":"South Tawton, Devon, England","England":"England","Castle Cary, Somersetshire, England":"Castle Cary, Somerset, England","South Taughton, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beaumont","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Gilles, Gaetan, Honore, Jacques, Jean-Guy, Marcel.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the five places in Normandy or several others elsewhere in France so named. The placename comes from Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>mont</i> ‘hill’. There are also places in England so named under Norman influence in Cumberland, Lancashire, and Essex, the last of which changed its name in the 12th century from <i>Fulepet</i> ‘foul pit’ to <i>Bealmont</i> ‘beautiful hill’; these may also have given rise to the surname. The surname is now widespread throughout England, but most common in Yorkshire. Compare   Belmont  .","History: Many English bearers of this surname are descended from Henry de Beaumont (died 1340), who came to England from France as a soldier, serving Kings Edward I, II, and III of England. He acquired the earldom of Buchan in Scotland by marriage. — Many American bearers of this surname are descendants of John Beaumont (1612–47), who came to North America from England in 1630. William Beaumont came from England to Cambridge MA in 1635 and subsequently moved to CT."],"variants":[{"name":"Bement","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire): variant of   Beaumont  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Beeman","meanings":["English (Kent): occupational name for a beekeeper, from Middle English <i>bee-man</i> ‘bee-keeper’ (Old English <i>bēo</i> + <i>mann</i>).","English (Kent): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German   Biemann   or of its Dutch cognate <b>Bieman</b>."]},{"name":"Belmont","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beaumont  .","Catalan: habitational name from the placename Bellmont ‘beautiful mountain’. Compare Spanish   Belmonte  ."]},{"name":"Baumunk","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Siegmund.","German: probably a Germanized form of a French Huguenot name <b>Beaumont</b> (see also   Beaumont  )."]},{"name":"Bayman","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German <b>Beumann</b> or <b>Bäumann</b>, variants of   Baumann  ."]}]},{"name":"Alicet","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":19,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Alicet Beaumont was born about 1240, in Devon, England as the daughter of Marguerite de Chabot. She married William de Cary in 1270, in Castle Cary, Somerset, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1273, in England, at the age of 34."},"et":{"about 1240–1273":"umbes 1240–1273","1240–1273":"1240–1273","1230–1303":"1230–1303","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","1270–1304":"1270–1304","1272–Male":"1272–Surnud","1273–Male":"1273–Surnud","1215–1240":"1215–1240","ABT 1260":"umbes 1260","1304":"1304","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1303":"1303","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1273":"1273","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","about 1240":"umbes 1240","Castle Cary,,,England":"Castle Cary, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","South Tawton, Devon, England":"South Tawton, Devon, England","England":"England","Castle Cary, Somersetshire, England":"Castle Cary, Somerset, England","South Taughton, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Devo